(Main Lesson) Tj
T*
(1. Introduction To The Topic) Tj
T*
(Tenses show the time of actions and help students write accurately. In a textbook) Tj
T*
(lesson, the first goal is to make the language idea clear. Students should be able to) Tj
T*
(explain what Tenses means, identify where it appears in English, and describe the main) Tj
T*
(purpose of the topic without relying on memorized sentences.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(2. Core Teaching) Tj
T*
(The central focus in Tenses is past, present, future, and consistent verb forms. This) Tj
T*
(means students must move beyond the overview and understand how the idea actually works.) Tj
T*
(A strong explanation should unpack the rules, relationships, or patterns behind Tenses) Tj
T*
(and show how those ideas guide correct answers. In English, success usually depends on) Tj
T*
(understanding the meaning, form, and effect that belong to the topic.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(3. How The Idea Is Applied) Tj
T*
(A useful way to teach Tenses is to connect the explanation directly to changing a) Tj
T*
(paragraph from present tense to past tense. That kind of language example shows students) Tj
T*
(how the topic moves from theory into use. At this stage, the learner should be able to) Tj
T*
(state the relevant rule or principle, explain why it fits the question, and then apply) Tj
T*
(the interpretation or writing method with confidence.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(4. Why Errors Happen) Tj
T*
(One common difficulty in Tenses is shifting tense halfway through a sentence or) Tj
T*
(paragraph. This matters because many learners can repeat a definition but still fail to) Tj
T*
(use it correctly. A real textbook lesson should therefore point out not only the correct) Tj
T*
